<h2>Alabama DOE Status of State Energy Codes</h2>
<br>
<B>Primary Technical Contact:</B><BR>


	Harvey McKim<BR>

	Alabama State Building Commission<BR>

	RSA Plaza 770 Washington Ave., Suite 444<BR>

	Montgomery, 

	AL  
36104<BR>

	PH:  (334) 242-4082  

	<BR>

	FX:  (334) 242-4182<BR>


<P><B>State Agency/Office Head:</B><BR>

Harvey A. McKim<br />
Alabama State Building Commission<br />
PH: (334) 242-4082<BR>


<P><B>Other Contact(s):</B><BR>

Terri L. Adams, Section Chief<br />
Department of Economic and Community Affairs<br />
PH: (334) 242-5333<BR>


<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>

Energy Codes of Alabama:  
<a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20020417130527/http://www.bsc.auburn.edu/aderhrw2/codes/">
http://www.bsc.auburn.edu/aderhrw2/codes/</a><BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
<p>Residential Energy Code for Alabama (RECA), a state developed code equivalent to the 1995 MEC is contingent upon local adoption.</p>

<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
<p>ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 for only state-owned or -funded buildings.</p>  

<p>With the exception of state-owned or -funded buildings, Alabama has not adopted a commercial energy code, nor does it have preemptive authority over units of local government for the establishment of a state energy code.   State-owned or -funded buildings are covered by the Alabama Building Energy Conservation Code (ABECC), which has prescriptive and performance based criteria that generally conform to ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989.</p>

<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>The state has made available a draft of the RECA 2000.  This voluntary code is based on the 1995 MEC.  Residential designers will be able to comly with RECA by following the prescriptive standards, by complying with the "Systems Analysis" approach specified in the 1995 MEC or by complying with the "Component Performance" approach specified in the 1995 Edition of the MEC.  The use of alternative analysis procedures, which meet the requirements of the 1995 MEC, may be accepted in lieu of the code.  The new code still needs to be okayed by the RECA Board, which is awaiting new appointments by the Governor.  (BCAP May/June 2000)</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

For other than state-owned or -funded buildings, local governement must adopt the code to be implemented.  The code is usually adopted through a vote of the city council or county commission.  Depending on the form of government, the mayor may be required to sign the law.  For state-funded buildings, the Alabama Building Commission must adopt revisions to the code.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

For state-owned or-funded buildings, the Alabama Building Commission reviews plans and specifications to ensure compliance.  For other buildings in localities that have adopted an energy code, compliance is addressed through the normal permit process.  Typically plans are submitted and reviewed and buildings are inspected during construction.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

For state-owned or -funded buildings, the design professional works with the Alabama Building Commission to establish compliance.  For other buildings, units of local government enforce compliance. If a local government adopts the 1995 MEC, the code requirements are enforced through the permit/inspection process for new construction and additions.  Depending on the size of the local government unit, the same office may perform plan reviews and inspections.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

Prior to July 31, 1995, cities and counties in Alabama were free to adopt energy codes as they deemed appropriate.  Most cities and counties that adopted an energy code adopted Appendix E of the 1994 Standard Building Code (SBC), or a prior edition of the SBC.  Chapter 13 of the 1994 SBC references Appendix E of the 1994 SBC, which in turn references the 1993  MEC.  Appendix E allows alternatives to complying with the 1995 MEC, which are ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 for commercial buildings and ANSI/ASHRAE/IES 90A-1980 and ASHRAE/IES 90B-1975 for residential buildings.

<p>On July 31, 1995, the Governor of Alabama signed House Bill (HB) 616.  HB 616 requires cities and counties that choose to adopt a residential building energy code to adopt the 1993 CABO MEC or its successors.  HB 616 defines the MEC as follows:  "The 1993 Edition of the Model Energy Code as prepared and maintained by the Council of American Building Officials, or any subsequent editions, changes, or recompilations thereof, or any other energy code, which the board has officially adopted."</p>

<p>HB 616 created the Alabama Residential Energy Code Board to promote the use and implementation of the MEC in Alabama.  The Board advises the Alabama Department of Economic and Community Affairs (ADECA) on implementation activities and provides for the mandatory implementation of and adherence to the MEC if a unit of local government so chooses to adopt it in whole or in part.</p>

<p>ADECA reported passage of the bill to the U.S. Department of Energy as part of their residential energy code certification under the Energy Policy Act of 1992 in a second certification letter dated August 8, 1995.</p><BR>


<P><B>State Energy Program (SEP) Grants Awarded:</B><BR>

<table width="550">
<tr>
	<td><B>Year</b></td><td><B>Amount</B></td><td><B>Description</B></td>
</tr>

<tr>
	<td valign=top>2000</td>
	<td valign=top NOWRAP>$ 86,440</td>
	<td valign=top>Implement an effort aimed at encouraging local jurisdictions in the State to adopt the voluntary Residential Energy Code of Alabama (RECA) in their local building codes by educating local building departments in the benefits of RECA, and working with them to adopt it as part of their local codes.  The project will also provide education to the housing industry regarding the benefits of building homes to meet RECA requirements and the use of construction practices that allow a builder to meet the code without incurring significant additional costs.   Source:  SEP Special Projects Selected for FY 2000 -  Report</td>
</tr>

<tr>
	<td valign=top>1996</td>
	<td valign=top NOWRAP>$ 98,887</td>
	<td valign=top>Assist communities to adopt the Residential Energy Code for Alabama, simplify ASHRAE Standard 90.1-1989 for adoption, and evaluate the support for a simplified commercial code.

</td>
</tr>
	
</table>


