<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>The local Department of Public Works is in the process of having the ICBO 1994 Uniform Building Code approved by the local legislature.  The American Samoa Energy Office (i.e., ASPA Energy Center), in joint cooperation with the Guam Energy Office, has obtained a federal grant under EPAct for technical assistance to develop a tropical island-specific model energy code.</p>

<p>This code will be designed to be easily applied and modified to meet not only Guam and American Samoa requirements, but also the requirements of other tropical island territories and nations.  The island-specific code would adopt cost-effective building energy technologies that meet or exceed the Council of American Building Officials (CABO) Model Energy Code (MEC) and ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989.</p>

<p>American Samoa completed development of a Commercial Building Energy Code in 1997.  From 1998-2000, the code process was tested by taking a government office building through the code process from plan review to occupancy.  American Samoa will not pursue adoption of the building energy code but will pursue development and adoption of an appropriate appliance standard for the entire territory.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

Standards are adopted through legislation.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

Not finalized.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

Not finalized.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

The Uniform Building Code is administered and enforced by the government public works department.<BR>


