<h2>Arizona DOE Status of State Energy Codes</h2>
<br>
<B>Primary Technical Contact:</B><BR>


	Jim Westberg<BR>

	Energy Program Administrator<BR>

	Arizona Department of Commerce<BR>

	Energy Office<BR>

	3800 N. Central Ave, Suite 1200<BR>

	Phoenix, 

	AZ  
85012<BR>

	PH:  (602) 280-1434  

	<BR>

	FX:  (602) 280-1445<BR>


<P><B>State Agency/Office Head:</B><BR>

Ms. Jackie Norton, Director<br />
Arizona Department of Commerce<br />
PH: (602) 280-1300<BR>


<P><B>Other Contact(s):</B><BR>

Charlie Gohman, Conservation & Engineering Manager<br />
Arizona Department of Commerce<br />
PH: (602) 280-1402<BR>


<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>

Energy Office:  
<a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20020417130527/http://www.azcommerce.com/energy.htm">
http://www.azcommerce.com/energy.htm</a>

<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
2000 IECC Voluntary statewide.<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1999 Voluntary statewide, except for state-owned or -funded buildings, which must comply with ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1999.<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>Some local jurisdictions, including Pima County and the City of Tucson, have adopted the 1995  Model Energy Code (MEC.)  A house bill was introduced in February 1999 to establish an energy code commission to look into a voluntary energy code for the state.  The bill would direct the commission to adopt by rule a voluntary energy code based on the 1998 International Energy Conservation Code (IECC), which in turn could be adopted by local municipalities.  The state is participating in a U.S. Department of Energy funded project with Utah and Nevada on energy code adoption and implementation as well as promoting energy efficiency standards above the 1995 MEC.</p>

<p>Legislation has been signed into law that establishes voluntary adoption of the 2000 IECC and ASHRAE 90.1-1999 statewide.  The legislation, House Bill 2541, also calls for the establishment of a State Energy Advisory Commission to review and make recommendations regarding the state energy code and to provide training and implementation strategies.  Tuscons/Pima county has adopted the 98 IECC, and Scottsdale is actively pursuing adoption of the 2000 IECC.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

No procedure exists for modifying the energy guidelines at the state level.  It is unlikely that a statewide code will be passed due to the independence of the local governments.  However, changes to the Arizona Fire Code (the only statewide mandatory code) are on a three-year code cycle corresponding with the publication of the International Conference of Building Officials Uniform Codes.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

Commercial:  For state-owned buildings, plans may be submitted to the Arizona Energy Office for review and comment.  However, submitting plans is not a mandatory requirement. No requirements exist for plan review or required inspections.

<p>Residential:  A home energy rating system is used for residential buildings.  This system is market-driven and is completely voluntary.  The local utility provides the compliance review and rating based on a points system.</p><BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

No mandatory energy inspection procedures exist at the state level for any building construction.  The Arizona Energy Office may review energy code requirements for state-owned commercial buildings if requested to do so by the responsible governmental agency.  No mandatory field inspections exist for state-owned commercial buildings.  Local enforcement agencies are responsible for enforcing local energy codes.  Note that some jurisdictions may adopt the International Conference of Building Officials Uniform Building Code and enforce energy requirements for non state-owned buildings.  For one- and two-family dwellings, the local utility provides the inspections required to ensure compliance with the Home Energy Rating<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

No mandatory statewide energy efficiency requirements for either residential or commercial buildings have existed except for state-owned commercial buildings.  All energy codes that do exist are adopted and enforced at the local level.

<p>The Arizona Guidelines for Energy Conservation in New Building Construction contained the mandatory minimum energy efficiency requirements for all state-owned commercial buildings that were heated and/or cooled.  However, plan reviews and inspections were not required at the state level.  Pima County, which encompasses the Tucson Metropolitan area, and the city of Tucson have adopted the 1995 MEC.</p><BR>


