<h2>Commonwealth of Puerto Rico DOE Status of State Energy Codes</h2>
<br>
<B>Primary Technical Contact:</B><BR>


	Lili Martinez<BR>

	Director of Government Programs<BR>

	Energy Affairs Administration<BR>

	Box 9066600<BR>

	Minillas Station<BR>

	Puerta de Tierra, 

	PR  
00906-6600<BR>

	PH:  (787) 723-3636  

	<BR>

	FX:  (787) 721-3089<BR>


<P><B>State Agency/Office Head:</B><BR>

Rafael Luis Llompart, Administrator<br />
Energy Affairs Administration<br />
PH: (787) 721-4370<BR>


<P><B>Other Contact(s):</B><BR>

Ann B. Gonzalez, PE<br />
Energy Affairs Administration<br />
PH: (787) 723-3636

<p>Rurico Diaz Aponte<br />
Energy Affairs Administration<br />
PH: (809) 723-3636</p><BR>


<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>


	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
The Code for Energy Conservation in Puerto Rico, based on ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989, is mandatory for the entire island of Puerto Rico.
<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
The Code for Energy Conservation in Puerto Rico, based on ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989, is mandatory for the entire island of Puerto Rico.
<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>The energy code applies to all new and remodeled buildings that have to comply with the Permits and Regulations Administration.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

The Commonwealth of Puerto Rico implements the code.  No revision schedule exists; all code revisions apply to all the entire island of Puerto Rico.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

All designs and plans must be submitted and signed by a professional engineer or architect.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

A certification by the professional who signs the plans is required.  No field inspections are made unless requested for special reasons.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

In 1979 the Code for Energy Conservation in Puerto Rico was adopted as part of the Building Codes administered by the Permits and Regulations Administration.  Legislation has been enacted that assigns the Energy Affairs Administration responsibility for updating the energy code.<BR>


