<P><B>State Agency/Office Head:</B><BR>

Juan B. Cepeda, Secretary<br />
Office of the Secretary<br />
Department of Public Works<br />
PH: 011 (670) 322-9481<BR>


<P><B>Other Contact(s):</B><BR>

Juan A. Camacho, Energy Director<br />
Department of Public Works<br />
PH: 011 (670) 664-4480<BR>


<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>


	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
State-developed code, which adopts the 1989 CABO One- and Two-Family Dwelling Code is mandatory for all new and remodeled residential buildings.
<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
State-developed code, which adopts the 1991 Uniform Building Code is mandatory for all new and remodeled multi-family and commercial buildings.
<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>Water Conservation System:  The Building Safety Official requires the construction of water catchment facilities in all buildings that must comply with the code.  To the greatest extent feasible, such catchments must be sized to provide adequate water to flush all toilets in the building.  The Building Safety Official is encouraged to approve alternative systems of sewage disposal that conserve potable water and meet all applicable public health standards.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

The Building Safety Code was developed through legislative action.  The rules and regulations governing the administrative procedures of the Building Safety Code were formulated by the Department of Public Works and were put up for Public Notice.  Changes in the code can only be made through legislative action.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

The Building Safety Code Division requires the submission of plans duly signed/stamped by an architect/engineer registered in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, together with the application for a building permit.  These plans are reviewed by the Plans Examiner for code compliance.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

The Building Safety Code Division in the Department of Public Works is the enforcing agency.  Field inspections are regularly conducted by certified building inspectors from the Building Safety Code Division to ensure compliance.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

The first Building Safety Code of the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands was enacted by the 6th Northern Marianas Commonwealth Legislature and was signed into Public Law on February 2, 1990.  The code adopts the 1991 Uniform Building Code, including Chapter 53 (for commercial and all multi-family buildings), and the 1989 Council of American Building Officials (CABO) One- and Two-Family Dwelling Code.  On January 2, 1992, the Building Safety Code was first enforced with the establishment of the Building Safety Code Division in the Department of Public Works.  The Building Safety Code Division processes an average of 250 building permit applications for multi-family residential and commercial buildings per year, and an average of 150 building permit applications for single-family dwellings per year.<BR>


