<h2>Idaho DOE Status of State Energy Codes</h2>
<br>
<B>Primary Technical Contact:</B><BR>


	Jack Rayne<BR>

	Building Programs Manager<BR>

	Division of Building Safety<BR>

	PO Box 83720<BR>

	Boise, 

	ID  
83720<BR>

	PH:  (208) 334-3896  

	<BR>

	FX:  (208) 334-5312<BR>


<P><B>State Agency/Office Head:</B><BR>

Dave Munroe, Administrator<br />
PH: (208) 334-3950<BR>


<P><B>Other Contact(s):</B><BR>


	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>


	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
Idaho Residential Energy Standard (IRES) , which is less stringent than the 1992 MEC.  The cities of Idaho Falls, Nampa, Lewiston, Coeur d'Alene, and Latah and Bingham Counties have adopted the 1995 MEC.  Also, the 1995 MEC is mandatory for all state-owned buildings.<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
Idaho Commercial Building Energy Code which is based on ASHRAE 90.1-1989 is voluntary statewide.  Can use modified COMcheck-EZ to show compliance.<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>ASHRAE/IESNA 90A-80 and 90B-1975 for state-owned buildings.</p>

<p>HB 611 passed the legislature and was signed by the Governor April 17.  The bill, which takes effect July 1, 2000, requires that any jurisdiction that has adopted the UBC adopt the most current version of the code, which is now the 1997 UBC.  In the past, a jurisdiction adopting the UBC could elect to leave out the appendix that included the energy code.  Draft propsed legislation to adopt the 200 IBC and possibly the 2000 IECC is in the discussion stage at present time.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

A review process was added by SB 1208.  No more often than every three years, the Idaho Building Contractors Association, with advice and consent from the Idaho Public Utilities Commission, names representatives from the utilities and the building industry to a panel.  The panel will also include representatives from Idaho's cities and counties and the Idaho Department of Water Resources.  The panel reviews IRES and recommends changes to the Idaho legislature.  Cities, counties, and the Idaho Department of Water Resources can choose their own representatives to serve on the review panel.  The panel makes recommendations to the Idaho Public Utilities Commission who in turn makes recommendations to the state legislature.

<p>Cities and counties may, but are not required to, adopt energy standards for commercial buildings and may modify the residential standards to be more restrictive without state approval.</p><BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

For state-owned buildings, compliance pathways and requirements for submitting plans are those in the 1995 MEC.  All low-rise residential structures are required to comply with the IRES unless a local code exists that is more stringent.  Where IRES is applicable and the local jurisdiction is enforcing the standard, the builder must complete and submit a "Builder Certification of Compliance" form to the local jurisdiction to show compliance.  In jurisdictions that are not enforcing the code, builders must provide a self-certification to the home buyer and to the jurisdiction if requested.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

IRES is enforced through a self-certification from the building contractor.  In jurisdictions that are enforcing IRES, the builder must complete and submit a Builder Certification of Compliance to the local enforcement agency prior to obtaining a building permit.   Local jurisdictions may also require a plan review and building inspections during the construction process.  Utilities are no longer involved in IRES enforcement, and a utility hookup permit is no longer required.

<p>Enforcement varies depending on whether the jurisdiction chooses to enforce IRES, has and enforces its own energy code (local alternative energy code), or elects not to enforce an energy code.</p>

<p>For jurisdictions that enforce a local alternative energy code (meaning any local energy code that has different provisions than IRES), such as the Boise & Ada County Energy Code with the special electric resistance path, the Bannock County Energy Code, the MEC, and the Northwest Energy Code, the following apply:
<ul>
<li>The builder must comply with IRES and give Indoor Air Quality notice to purchaser or occupants.</li>
<li>The builder certification to jurisdiction is required.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction must supply builder certification forms.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may charge up to $25 for supplying certifications forms.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction must enforce the energy code the same way that it enforces its building code -- the means of enforcement is "without limitation" and no fees or fee limits are mentioned.</li></ul>
</p>
<p>For jurisdictions with local enforcement (meaning the local jurisdiction does not have an alternative energy code and enforces IRES with or without a local ordinance that adopts or refers to IRES), the following apply:
<ul>
<li>The builder must comply with IRES and give indoor air quality notice to purchaser or occupants.</li>
<li>The builder must certify compliance to potential purchasers.</li>
<li>The builder must certify compliance to the jurisdiction if requested.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may elect to provide IRES certification forms.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may charge up to $25 per form for certification forms.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may elect to provide IRES inspections.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may charge up to $50 for an IRES inspection.</li></ul></p>

<p>For jurisdictions with no local energy code enforcement (meaning the local jurisdiction does not have an alternative energy code and does not enforce IRES locally), the following apply:
<ul>
<li>The builder must comply with IRES and give indoor air Quality notice to purchaser or occupants.</li>
<li>The builder must certify compliance to potential purchasers.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may elect to provide IRES certification forms.</li>
<li>The jurisdiction may charge up to $25 per form for certification forms.</li></ul></p>

<p>Certification forms must be substantially the same as stated in 44-2304.  The stated form refers to a "U-Value Trade-Off Graph" listed in Box 3, but no graph or Box 3 is in the statute.  These references are to items in the old IRES rules and forms.  A local jurisdiction can customize the form and eliminate the "Alternate Prescriptive" lines if it chooses.</p>

<p>The builders are now included in the release from liability arising from indoor air quality if they "construct ..to the energy-efficient construction standards set forth in this chapter ," meaning at least the minimum envelope requirements, air leakage control, duct leakage, fireplace and stove measures, and ventilation requirements of 44-2302(1)(c).  Plus, builders may be required to prove the required indoor air quality notice was provided to the purchaser or occupants.  The notice that used to be in the rules is now in the statute.  It does not refer to carbon monoxide as a type of indoor air pollution.</p><BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

IRES (Senate Bill [SB] 1591) was enacted in 1990 and was the only legislated statewide energy code in Idaho.  However, it was a minimum standard and local jurisdictions could adopt more stringent energy codes.

<p>A 1994 state-sponsored analysis of new construction by jurisdiction and energy code indicated that approximately 38% of housing starts were built to IRES.  The five different energy codes listed below were used in the state as of late 1994:
<ul>
<li>Idaho Residential Energy Standard (IRES)</li>
<li>Northwest Energy Code (NEC), adopted by 46 jurisdictions</li>
<li>Bannock County Energy Code (BCEC), based on the NEC</li>
<li>Boise City and Ada County energy code, based on the NEC</li>
<li>IDWR's fuel-blind code for non electrically heated homes, adopted by Lewiston.</li></ul></p>

<p>Senate Bill 1208 was passed in March 1995 modifying the 1990 IRES to the 1996 IRES, which became effective January 1, 1996.  The 1996 IRES eliminates the requirement for builder certification to the Department of Labor and Industrial Services in cities or counties that have not adopted the IRES or an alternate code.</p><BR>


