	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

The primary energy conservation law in Illinois was the Illinois Public Utilities Act (revised in 1986.)  This law required Illinois investor-owned electric utilities to use least-cost energy planning, which required the use of economical energy conservation when new resources for electicity were required.  This requirement was implemented by utilities and monitored by the Illinois Commerce Commission through the least-cost energy planning process.  The requirement for utility energy conservation programs was in part the result of rate-payer frustration over the untimely and costly construction of several nuclear power plants in the late 1970s and early 1980s.  

<p>These provisions are no longer in effect.</p><BR>


