<h2>Kansas DOE Status of State Energy Codes</h2>
<br>
<B>Primary Technical Contact:</B><BR>


	Jim Ploger<BR>

	Energy Program Manager<BR>

	Kansas Corporation Commission<BR>

	Energy Programs<BR>

	1500 S.W. Arrowhead Road<BR>

	Topeka, 

	KS  
66604-4027<BR>

	PH:  (785) 271-3170  

	<BR>

	FX:  (785) 271-3268<BR>


<P><B>State Agency/Office Head:</B><BR>

John Wine, Chair<br />
Kansas Corporation Commission<br />
PH: (785) 271-3166<BR>


<P><B>Other Contact(s):</B><BR>

Larry Holoway, Chief Engineer<br />
Kansas Corporation Commission<br />
PH: (785) 271-3222<BR>


<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>

Kansas Corporation Commission (KCC):  <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20020417130527/http://www.kcc.state.ks.us/energy/energy.htm">http://www.kcc.state.ks.us/energy/energy.htm</a><BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
1993 MEC or energy-efficiency disclosure form is mandatory statewide; can use MECcheck to show compliance.<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 is mandatory statewide; can use COMcheck to show compliance.<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>

	Not Available<BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

Legislative action would be required to amend the code adopted by the state.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

The statewide energy standards require an energy efficiency disclosure by the builder or seller of new residential buildings to the buyer.  The disclosure provides the energy attributes of the structure.  The MECcheck compliance materials developed by the U.S. Department of Energy are one of several ways to show compliance with the 1993 MEC.  No formal plan review or construction inspection is required.  The potential for litigation exists as a way to ensure compliance for commercial and industrial buildings.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

Local jurisdictions do not enforce the statewide energy standards.  The state conducts enforcement activities for state-owned buildings.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

During the 1975, 1976, and 1977 legislative sessions, both the Kansas Legislative Special Committee on Energy and Natural Resources and the Kansas House Committee on Energy and Natural Resources considered bills that would have enacted statewide building codes addressing energy efficiency.  These legislative attempts failed, and in 1977 the House Committee abandoned an attempt to pass a bill in favor of allowing the KCC to address the issue in a Show Cause Order issued under Docket 110,766-U.  Thermal standards as well as air-conditioning equipment efficiency were subsequently adopted by the Kansas Corporation Commission order in September 1977 under Docket 110,766-U.  Under the order, each electric and gas utility under the jurisdiction of the KCC was to require a certificate of compliance with the adopted standards from the owner of each newly constructed residential or commercial building before the utility could provide permanent service.

<p>The thermal standards (maximum heat loss as a function of floor area) adopted at that time presented a problem because not all electric and gas utilities were under KCC's jurisdiction.  To address that concern, the 1978 legislative session adopted Kansas Statutes Annotated 66-131a, HB 2698, giving the KCC jurisdiction over municipal electric and natural gas utilities to restrict connections to buildings not meeting the standards.</p>

<p>Gas utilities were only required to ensure compliance with the insulation requirements of the order, while electric utilities were required to ensure compliance with both the insulation and air-conditioning equipment efficiency requirements.   In 1979 the legislature approved the adoption of Kansas Administrative Regulation 27-2-1, establishing maximum lighting efficiency standards for public buildings.</p>

<p>The thermal standards were in effect for all Kansas electric and natural gas utilities until 1992.  The 1992 legislative session adopted Kansas Statutes Annotated 66-104d, SB 435, which allowed electric cooperatives the option of deregulation.  Since that time, some electric utilities have exercised this option and are no longer under KCC's jurisdiction.  Other than the jurisdictional modification in 1992, there have been no revisions or updates to the statewide energy standards adopted under the order since 1980.  Some of the larger cities and counties did establish and enforce their own energy standards.</p>

<p>The KCC formally adopted the 1993 MEC and ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 on January 23, 1996.  Formal orders were to be issued within 60 days following adoption.  Utilities under KCC authority were given 12 months to implement the new order.</p>

<p>HB 2707 was introduced in 1996 and would have eliminated KCC's authority to adopt and enhance energy efficiency standards for residential construction.  This bill was not enacted in 1996.</p>

<p>Senate Bill 74 introduced in 1997 proposed to eliminate KCC's authority to adopt or enforce residential energy standards, thereby repealing the 1993 MEC for residential construction.  This bill died in the Senate Committee on Energy and Natural Resources on March 1, 1997.</p>

<p>House Bill (HB) 2140 was introduced in 1997 to repeal the 1993 MEC and KCC's authority to adopt and enforce residential energy standards.  It also required disclosure to the buyers of new homes of the R-values and U-values of installed insulation, windows and doors, and all HVAC and water heating equipment efficiencies to new home buyers.  The bill was defeated.</p>

<p>On April 24, 1997, Kansas Governor Bill Graves signed legislation (SB 333) to retain the 1993 MEC for residential construction referenced in the state energy efficiency policy.  In addition, Section 17 of SB 333 adopted ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 (standard or code) for new commercial and industrial structures, although it did not define "commercial" or "industrial."  The legislature, through Section 17, also assumed authority for building energy standards from the KCC.  Both the 1993 MEC and ASHRAE 90.1-1989 are mandatory throughout the state.  SB 333 retains the authority of local government to adopt and enforce standards that are more stringent than the state standards.</p>

<p>The KCC is still responsible for commercial and residential energy code training and educational seminars.</p><BR>


