<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>
NO<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>The state building code's energy provisions contain mandatory minimum requirements for all newly constructed buildings and additions that are heated and/or mechanically cooled.  This provision also applies to state-owned and -operated buildings and all alterations and repairs to existing buildings.</p>

<p>The state amended the MEC by incorporating a prescriptive thermal envelope option (minimum building component R-values) to the thermal requirements in Section 502 of the Council of American Building Officials Model Energy Code (MEC).  This option provides prescriptive and equivalent R-values as follows:</p>

<table border="4">
<tr>
 <td></td>
 <td><b>Equivalent<br />Path</b></td>
 <td><b>Prescriptive<br />Path</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Ceiling</td>
 <td>R-38</td>
 <td>R-42</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Walls</td>
 <td>R-19</td>
 <td>R-21</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Floors over unheated space</td>
 <td>R-19</td>
 <td>R-19</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Basement walls</td>
 <td>R-10</td>
 <td>R-11</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Foundation</td>
 <td>R-19</td>
 <td>R-19</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Doors</td>
 <td>R-2</td>
 <td>R-5</td>
</tr>
<tr>
 <td>Windows</td>
 <td>U-0.4</td>
 <td>U-0.5</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>*Basement wall insultation below uninsulated floors, except for rim joists and perimeter cripple walls, may be delayed until such time as the basement is actually finished for occupancy.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

Local government code enforcement jurisdictions have 90 days to adopt the state building code once they receive notification from the state of change to the code.  If an approved local government code enforcement program does not exist, the State Building Codes Division enforces the applicable codes.  Three counties and 48 incorporated cities have adopted the state energy code.  The energy codes are reviewed on a three-year cycle corresponding to the adoption of new versions of the International Conference of Building Officials (ICBO) Uniform Codes.  Proposed changes are submitted to the Building Codes Division.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

The builder must provide a labeling sticker.  The label must be permanent and placed on the interior electrical panel.  The R-values and U-values provided for building envelope components and mechanical equipment efficiency must be shown on the label.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

When required by the building official, plans and specifications must be submitted.  The building official may also require that plans and specifications be prepared by a licensed architect or engineer.  A registered architect or engineer must prepare all Chapter 4 (MEC) submissions.  When the State Building Codes Division enforces the code, Section 105.2 of the MEC is not applicable.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

Montana first adopted a statewide building code in 1972 with the adoption of the ICBO Uniform Codes.  Montana adopted the appendix of Chapter 53 (Energy) referenced in the 1985 Uniform Building Code, which referenced the 1983 MEC.

<p>The state adopted the 1993 MEC with minimal changes as the statewide energy code on February 9, 1996.</p><BR>


