<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>South Dakota's EPAct response requests a two-year extension to consider updating its codes and is requesting an additional year to complete an economic impact study.</p>

<p>Future plans include attempts to adopt the 1992 Council of American Building Officials (CABO) Model Energy Code (MEC) as the statewide residential standard and the ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 standards for commercial buildings.  These proposals must first be processed through the state legislature.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

Changes to the state building code must first be processed through the state legislature.  Changes are processed on a three-year code cycle corresponding with the publication of the Uniform Codes.  Local jurisdictions may adopt energy requirements without state approval.  Only larger jurisdictions have elected to do so at this time.<BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

Compliance with local codes is decided by local jurisdictions.<BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

An energy code is not enforced at the state level.  If a local energy code is adopted, it is enforced at the local level.<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

In 1978 when the South Dakota building code was first enacted, an energy code was part of Chapter 53 of the state building code.  However, only three jurisdictions adopted the energy code portion of the state building code.  As of 1994, no jurisdictions actively enforced the energy code portion of the state building code.<BR>


