<P><B>State website(s):</B><BR>

Virginia Division of Energy:  <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20020417130527/http://www.mme.state.va.us/de/">http://www.mme.state.va.us/de/</a><BR>


<P><B>Current Status Residential:</B><BR>
State building code, which adopts the 1995 MEC by reference, is mandatory statewide; can use MECcheck to show compliance.
<BR>


<P><B>Can use MECcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Residential Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Commercial:</B><BR>
ASHRAE/IESNA 90.1-1989 is mandatory statewide; can use COMcheck to show compliance.<BR>


<P><B>Can use COMcheck to show compliance:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Commercial Energy Code is mandatory statewide:</B><BR>
YES<BR>


<P><B>Current Status Notes:</B><BR>
<p>The Virginia Uniform Statewide Building Code (VUSBC) is a statewide minimum requirement that local jurisdictions cannot amend.  The code is applicable to all new buildings in the commonwealth.  The VUSBC requires that any new construction (addition) to existing buildings comply with the requirements of the 1995 MEC; unaltered portions of the building are not required to comply.</p><BR>


<P><B>Adoption Process:</B><BR>

Virginia adopts the Building Officials and Code Administrators (BOCA) International, National Building Code a year after the publication year by BOCA (which occurs every three years.)  The Board of Housing and Community Development (a Governor-appointed board) has authority to adopt changes to the VUSBC.  The process is very similar to the federal regulatory process.  The Board of Housing and Community Development may adopt whatever provision it deems necessary.  The adoption process for modifications may take 12 months.  Publications include new provisions and modifications to the code.  Public hearings are also included in the process.

<p>The General Assembly also promulgates requirements for the VUSBC.  These requirements ONLY apply to state buildings.  The scope of these provisions are items such as asbestos removal and minimum temperature settings that are not addressed in the VUSBC.</p><BR>


<P><B>Compliance Method:</B><BR>

Compliance for non state buildings is demonstrated through plan review and inspection at the local level.

<p>The Director of the Virginia Department of General Services, acting through the Division of Engineering and Buildings, acts as the code official for state buildings.  This office performs plan reviews and construction inspections for all state buildings.</p><BR>


<P><B>Enforcement:</B><BR>

The local building department enforces the VUSBC requirements through plan reviews and inspections.  An appeal to the code official's decision is also handled at the local level.  The Virginia Statewide Building Code Technical Review Board is responsible for official interpretations of the VUSBC.  The board meets to review a request for interpretation upon receipt.  Other interested and affected parties have an opportunity to participate in the interpretation.  It generally takes 90 days for an interpretation to be approved.  Official interpretations are published in the Virginia Department of Housing and Community Development monthly newsletter and serve to clarify certain provisions of the Uniform Statewide Building Code.  An official interpretation is considered law and must be enforced by the applicable state and local agencies<BR>


<P><B>Background/History:</B><BR>

Virginia adopted the VUSBC in 1973, a statewide building code based on the BOCA Basic Codes.  The statewide requirements cannot be modified by local jurisdictions.  Prior to 1973, local government was free to adopt codes.  The current statewide building code adopts the 1995 MEC by reference for energy efficiency criteria, effective April 15, 1997.<BR>


